---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import PrincipleBanner from '../components/PrincipleBanner.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import WhyBox from '../components/WhyBox.astro';
import InsightBox from '../components/InsightBox.astro';
import CardGrid from '../components/CardGrid.astro';
import Card from '../components/Card.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Steps from '../components/Steps.astro';
import ProgressOverview from '../components/ProgressOverview.astro';
import ArchDiagram from '../components/ArchDiagram.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const failureLoopSteps = [
  {
    title: 'Agent makes a mistake',
    desc: 'The agent produces incorrect code, violates a convention, or makes a wrong assumption. This is normal and expected.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Fix the immediate issue',
    desc: 'Correct the code. Do not just move on — this is the trigger for the improvement loop.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Log it in docs/failure-log.md',
    desc: 'Record what happened, why it happened, and what rule would prevent it. This builds institutional memory.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Add or update a rule in docs/rules/',
    desc: 'Write the rule that would have prevented the mistake. Be specific and prescriptive.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Run scripts/sync-rules.sh',
    desc: 'Propagate the new rule to all AI tools automatically. Every agent now knows the rule.',
  },
  {
    title: 'That mistake never happens again',
    desc: 'The rule is now part of the harness. Every future agent session starts with this knowledge already loaded.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout>
  <Hero />
  <PrincipleBanner />

  <div class="content">

    <!-- ── INTRO ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="what-is-this">
      <SectionHeader
        label="What Is This?"
        title="A system for making AI agents reliable"
        subtitle="Harness Engineering is the practice of encoding everything an AI agent needs to know directly into the repository — so it can work autonomously without constant human guidance."
      />

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          When you first start using AI coding agents, you probably chat with them: &ldquo;Hey,
          can you add a button here?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Fix this bug.&rdquo; The agent helps, you
          review, you move on. This works fine for small tasks.
        </p>
        <p>
          But as projects grow, this approach breaks down. Every new agent session starts cold
          &mdash; the agent has no memory of what you built yesterday, what rules you follow, or
          what mistakes were made last week. You end up re-explaining the same things over and over.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Harness Engineering solves this.</strong> Instead of relying on conversation to
          transfer knowledge, we encode that knowledge directly into the repository. The agent reads
          the repo, understands the project, and can work autonomously &mdash; following the right
          rules, avoiding known mistakes, and picking up tasks without hand-holding.
        </p>
      </div>

      <ProgressOverview />
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── FIRST PRINCIPLES ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="first-principles">
      <SectionHeader
        label="First Principles"
        title="Why harness engineering works"
        subtitle="Three foundational insights that explain why encoding knowledge into the repository is the right model for AI-assisted development."
      />

      <div class="principles-list">

        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-number">01</div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <h3 class="principle-title">The agent sees only the repository</h3>
            <p>
              This is the foundational insight everything else builds on. From the agent&rsquo;s point
              of view, anything it can&rsquo;t access in-context while running effectively doesn&rsquo;t
              exist. Knowledge that lives in Google Docs, chat threads, or people&rsquo;s heads is not
              accessible to the system.
            </p>
            <p>
              Think of it like onboarding a new hire who can never attend meetings, never use Slack,
              and never ask a colleague a question. The only thing they can see is the git repository.
              If the information isn&rsquo;t in the repo, it doesn&rsquo;t exist for the agent. That
              Slack discussion where your team aligned on an architectural pattern? If it&rsquo;s not
              discoverable to the agent, it might as well have never happened.
            </p>
            <p>
              This flips the traditional engineering mindset. Normally, knowledge is distributed across
              people, wikis, chat threads, and tribal memory. Harness engineering demands you externalize
              everything into the repo itself &mdash; as versioned, machine-readable artifacts.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-number">02</div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <h3 class="principle-title">The human&rsquo;s job changes</h3>
            <p>
              Throughout the development process, humans never directly contributed any code. This
              became a core philosophy: no manually-written code. The lack of hands-on human coding
              introduced a different kind of engineering work, focused on systems, scaffolding, and
              leverage.
            </p>
            <p>
              This is the paradigm shift. The engineer&rsquo;s job moves from writing code to three
              new responsibilities: designing environments for agents to work in, specifying intent
              clearly enough for agents to act on, and building feedback loops that catch mistakes
              mechanically.
            </p>
            <p>
              When something failed, the fix was almost never &ldquo;try harder.&rdquo; Because the
              only way to make progress was to get the agent to do the work, human engineers always
              stepped into the task and asked: &ldquo;what capability is missing, and how do we make
              it both legible and enforceable for the agent?&rdquo;
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="principle-card">
          <div class="principle-number">03</div>
          <div class="principle-body">
            <h3 class="principle-title">Constraints make agents better, not worse</h3>
            <p>
              This is counterintuitive but critical. Paradoxically, constraining the solution space
              makes agents more productive, not less. You know this from your LLM experience &mdash; a
              model given a vague prompt produces vague output. A model told &ldquo;respond only in
              JSON with these exact fields&rdquo; produces more reliable output.
            </p>
            <p>
              Harness engineering extends this principle to the entire working environment. Every rule,
              every boundary test, every structured plan is a constraint that narrows the space of
              possible actions &mdash; and in doing so, makes the agent&rsquo;s output more
              predictable, more correct, and more useful.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 1 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase1">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 1"
        title="The Map — AGENTS.md"
        subtitle="Give every AI agent a complete orientation to the project in a single file it reads at the start of every session."
        phase={1}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          Every AI agent session started completely cold &mdash; the agent had no idea what the
          project was about, which directories mattered, or what rules to follow. A human had to
          explain everything from scratch every single time. This was like hiring a new employee
          every day and re-onboarding them from zero.
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The solution was <code>AGENTS.md</code> at the project root &mdash; a ~100-line
          &ldquo;table of contents&rdquo; for every AI agent. Think of it as the README that no
          human reads but every agent <em>must</em> read. It covers everything the agent needs
          to orient itself instantly:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>What the project is and how it is structured</li>
          <li>Where the rules live (so agents know what to follow)</li>
          <li>Key commands to run (so agents do not guess)</li>
          <li>Architecture rules that must never be broken</li>
          <li>What to do when a mistake happens</li>
          <li>Known technical debt (so agents do not accidentally make it worse)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Why a single file instead of scattered documentation?</h4>
        <p>
          AI agents work within a <strong>context window</strong> &mdash; a fixed amount of text
          they can &ldquo;see&rdquo; at one time. Every file they open consumes part of that window.
          If project knowledge is spread across dozens of files, the agent has to make choices about
          what to read and what to skip. It will inevitably miss something important.
        </p>
        <p>
          <code>AGENTS.md</code> solves this by compressing the most critical orientation into a
          single file that fits entirely within one context window read. The agent doesn&rsquo;t
          need to hunt for information &mdash; it gets the full map in one pass. From there, it
          knows <em>where</em> to go for more detail (e.g., <code>docs/rules/</code> for coding
          conventions, <code>docs/plans/</code> for feature specifications).
        </p>

        <h4>How to write an effective AGENTS.md</h4>
        <p>
          The key discipline is <strong>brevity with pointers</strong>. The file itself should not
          contain full rule definitions or architecture specifications &mdash; those live in
          dedicated files. Instead, <code>AGENTS.md</code> contains short summaries and file paths.
          Think of it as a table of contents, not an encyclopedia.
        </p>
        <p>
          A common mistake is letting <code>AGENTS.md</code> grow past 150 lines. When this happens,
          the file starts competing with itself for attention in the context window. Ruthlessly prune
          anything that can be a pointer instead of inline content. If a section takes more than 5
          lines to explain, it belongs in its own file with a one-line reference from
          <code>AGENTS.md</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The best <code>AGENTS.md</code> files evolve organically. Start with the basics &mdash;
          project purpose, directory layout, and key commands. Then, every time an agent makes a
          mistake because it lacked context, ask: &ldquo;Would a one-line entry in AGENTS.md have
          prevented this?&rdquo; If yes, add it. Over weeks, the file naturally converges on exactly
          the information agents need most.
        </p>
      </div>

      <CardGrid>
        <Card icon="🗺️" title="Project Structure" tag="AGENTS.md">
          Maps every important directory so the agent knows where things live without exploring
          blindly.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="📜" title="Rules Index" tag="docs/rules/">
          Points to <code>docs/rules/</code> so agents always know where authoritative coding rules
          are stored.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="⚙️" title="Key Commands" tag="mix, npm">
          Lists the exact commands to compile, test, lint, and reset the database &mdash; no
          guessing required.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🚫" title="Architecture Invariants" tag="CI enforced">
          Documents the rules that must never be broken, like Core never importing from tenant
          modules.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="📝" title="Failure Log Template" tag="docs/failure-log.md">
          A template for logging agent mistakes so they seed the improvement loop in Phase 4.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="⚠️" title="Known Tech Debt" tag="boundary violations">
          Documents existing boundary violations so agents do not accidentally make them worse.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          Keeping AGENTS.md under 120 lines means the entire file fits in one AI context window
          read &mdash; the agent gets the full picture instantly. A longer file would get skimmed
          or truncated. Brevity is a feature, not a limitation.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 2 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase2">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 2"
        title="Consolidate Rules Authority"
        subtitle="One source of truth for all coding rules, automatically distributed to every AI tool."
        phase={2}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          Rules for how to write code existed in 4 different directories (<code>.cursor/rules/</code
          >, <code>.agent/rules/</code>, <code>.roo/rules/</code>, <code>.gemini/</code>). Each AI
          tool read from its own directory. Over time, these drifted apart &mdash; Cursor agents saw
          different rules than Roo agents. Updating a rule meant editing 4 files and hoping you did
          not miss one.
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The solution was <code>docs/rules/</code> as the single source of truth. A script (<code
            >scripts/sync-rules.sh</code
          >) generates all the tool-specific rule files automatically. Git hooks regenerate them
          whenever you pull or switch branches.
        </p>
        <p>
          Think of it like a database with one source &mdash; you edit one file, and all tools get
          the update automatically. It is impossible to have drift because the generated files are
          never committed to git.
        </p>

        <h4>Why rules drift is so dangerous</h4>
        <p>
          When different AI tools see different rules, bugs become <em>invisible</em>. Imagine
          Cursor follows the rule &ldquo;always use parameterized queries&rdquo; but Roo&rsquo;s
          copy of that rule was accidentally deleted. Roo generates raw SQL. The code looks fine in
          Roo&rsquo;s context. The developer trusts the agent. A SQL injection vulnerability ships
          to production. The root cause wasn&rsquo;t the agent &mdash; it was rule drift between
          tool configurations.
        </p>
        <p>
          This scenario gets worse over time. Each tool accumulates small differences: a rule
          phrased slightly differently here, a missing rule there, conflicting advice between two
          tools. Eventually, the rules become unreliable across the board and developers stop
          trusting any of them. Consolidation prevents this erosion of trust.
        </p>

        <h4>How the sync pipeline works</h4>
        <p>
          Each rule file in <code>docs/rules/</code> is a Markdown file with YAML frontmatter.
          The frontmatter contains metadata like <code>scope</code> (which files the rule applies
          to), <code>trigger</code> (when the AI tool should activate it), and <code>description</code>
          (a one-line summary). The sync script reads these files and transforms them into the
          format each AI tool expects.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, Cursor expects rules in <code>.cursor/rules/*.mdc</code> with a specific
          frontmatter format. Roo expects them in <code>.roo/rules/*.md</code> with a different
          format. The sync script handles these transformations automatically. You never think about
          format differences &mdash; you just write the rule once in plain Markdown, and the script
          does the rest.
        </p>
        <p>
          Git hooks ensure the sync runs automatically. A <code>post-merge</code> hook regenerates
          tool-specific files after every <code>git pull</code>. A <code>post-checkout</code> hook
          does the same on branch switches. The generated files are listed in <code>.gitignore</code>
          so they never pollute the repository &mdash; they exist only on each developer&rsquo;s
          local machine, always freshly generated from the single source.
        </p>

        <h4>Writing effective rules</h4>
        <p>
          The best rules are <strong>specific, prescriptive, and testable</strong>. A vague rule
          like &ldquo;write clean code&rdquo; gives an agent nothing actionable. A specific rule
          like &ldquo;all Ecto queries must use <code>Repo.all/1</code> with explicit preloads;
          never use lazy loading&rdquo; tells the agent exactly what to do and what to avoid.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rules should also include <strong>examples</strong> where possible. AI agents learn
          patterns from examples even more effectively than from abstract instructions. A rule that
          says &ldquo;do X&rdquo; accompanied by a code snippet showing X is dramatically more
          effective than the instruction alone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <CardGrid>
        <Card icon="📂" title="docs/rules/ (Source)" tag="source of truth">
          The single canonical location for all coding rules. Edit here, and everything else updates
          automatically.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🔄" title="sync-rules.sh" tag="scripts/sync-rules.sh">
          A script that reads <code>docs/rules/</code> and generates the correct format for each AI
          tool automatically.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🪝" title="Git Hooks" tag="auto-generated">
          Automatically regenerate tool-specific rule files on every pull and branch switch &mdash;
          zero manual steps.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🏷️" title="Rule Metadata" tag="frontmatter">
          Each rule file has scope and trigger metadata so tools know when to apply each rule
          automatically.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>

      <CodeBlock html={`<span class="cm"># docs/rules/ is the only place you edit</span>
<span class="fi">docs/rules/elixir.md</span>          <span class="cm"># Backend Elixir conventions</span>
<span class="fi">docs/rules/ecto.md</span>            <span class="cm"># Database query patterns</span>
<span class="fi">docs/rules/frontend-core.md</span>   <span class="cm"># React 19 patterns</span>
<span class="fi">docs/rules/global.md</span>          <span class="cm"># Rules for ALL code</span>

<span class="cm"># Generated automatically (never edit directly):</span>
<span class="fi">.cursor/rules/elixir.mdc</span>      <span class="ar">← generated by sync-rules.sh</span>
<span class="fi">.agent/rules/elixir.md</span>        <span class="ar">← generated by sync-rules.sh</span>
<span class="fi">.roo/rules/elixir.md</span>          <span class="ar">← generated by sync-rules.sh</span>`} />

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          Rules are now like a database with one source &mdash; you edit one file, and all tools get
          the update automatically. It is impossible to have drift because the generated files are
          never committed to git. The sync script is the only path from source to output.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 3 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase3">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 3"
        title="Deterministic Constraints"
        subtitle="Turn architecture rules from documentation into automated tests that fail the build when violated."
        phase={3}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          The architecture rules (like &ldquo;Core code must never import from the FH tenant
          module&rdquo;) were documented but not enforced. An AI agent could violate them and nobody
          would catch it until a human reviewer noticed. Review comments for the same structural
          violations kept repeating.
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The solution was automated tests that run in CI (Continuous Integration) and fail the
          build if architecture rules are violated. These tests make violations
          <em>mechanically impossible to merge</em> &mdash; no human review required.
        </p>

        <h4>The spectrum of enforcement</h4>
        <p>
          There&rsquo;s a hierarchy of how strongly a rule can be enforced, from weakest to strongest:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Tribal knowledge</strong> &mdash; someone on the team knows the rule and mentions it in code review. Weakest because it depends on that person being available and reviewing every PR.</li>
          <li><strong>Written documentation</strong> &mdash; the rule exists in a wiki, README, or <code>AGENTS.md</code>. Better, but agents can miss it or misinterpret it.</li>
          <li><strong>AI tool rules</strong> (Phase 2) &mdash; the rule is loaded into the agent&rsquo;s context automatically. Much better, but the agent can still choose to violate it.</li>
          <li><strong>Automated tests in CI</strong> (this phase) &mdash; the rule is checked mechanically on every commit. Strongest because violation physically prevents merging.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Phase 3 targets the top of this hierarchy. Not every rule needs a CI test &mdash; convention
          preferences like &ldquo;prefer <code>const</code> over <code>let</code>&rdquo; are fine as
          Phase 2 rules. But <strong>architecture invariants</strong> &mdash; the rules where violation
          would cause structural damage to the codebase &mdash; must be at level 4. If it would take
          days to untangle a violation, it deserves a deterministic test.
        </p>

        <h4>What makes a good boundary test</h4>
        <p>
          Boundary tests are different from unit tests. They don&rsquo;t test behavior &mdash; they
          test <em>structure</em>. A boundary test scans source files (often using simple string
          matching or AST parsing) and verifies that certain import patterns, module references, or
          code structures do or do not exist.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, a boundary test for a multi-tenant application might scan every file in
          <code>lib/core/</code> and assert that none of them contain <code>import</code> or
          <code>alias</code> statements referencing <code>FH.</code> (the tenant-specific namespace).
          This is a simple regex scan &mdash; not complex test infrastructure &mdash; but it
          provides an ironclad guarantee that core code stays independent of tenant code.
        </p>
        <p>
          The beauty of these tests is that they&rsquo;re <strong>cheap to write and expensive to
          violate</strong>. A 20-line test script can enforce an architecture rule that would otherwise
          require constant vigilance from human reviewers. And unlike human reviewers, the test never
          gets tired, never misses a file, and never approves a violation because &ldquo;it&rsquo;s
          just this once.&rdquo;
        </p>

        <h4>Beyond import boundaries</h4>
        <p>
          Boundary tests aren&rsquo;t limited to import checking. Common patterns include:
          <strong>API envelope tests</strong> that verify every HTTP response wraps data in a
          consistent structure; <strong>naming convention tests</strong> that ensure all database
          migration files follow a specific naming pattern; and <strong>dependency direction tests</strong>
          that verify the dependency graph flows in one direction (e.g., UI &rarr; API &rarr; DB,
          never the reverse). Each of these is a structural invariant that, once violated, creates
          compounding maintenance costs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <CardGrid>
        <Card icon="🧪" title="Elixir Boundary Test" tag="boundary_test.exs">
          Scans all backend files to ensure Core modules never reference FH (tenant) modules. Fails
          CI if violated.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="⚛️" title="Frontend Boundary Test" tag="imports.test.ts">
          Scans all frontend files to ensure core UI never imports from tenant UI. Enforces the same
          separation in TypeScript.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="📦" title="API Envelope Test" tag="api_envelope_test.exs">
          Verifies all API responses are wrapped in the correct <code>{'{ data: ... }'}</code> format.
          Catches structural regressions automatically.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          &ldquo;Mechanically impossible to merge&rdquo; is stronger than &ldquo;documented in a
          rule.&rdquo; If the CI build fails, the violation cannot be merged &mdash; no human review
          required. Documentation tells people what to do; tests enforce it whether they read the
          docs or not.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 4 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase4">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 4"
        title="The Failure Loop"
        subtitle="Convert every agent mistake into a permanent rule that prevents that mistake from ever happening again."
        phase={4}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          When an AI agent made a mistake, the fix was applied to the code but rarely to the rules
          that would prevent the mistake from happening again. The same categories of errors kept
          recurring because there was no systematic process to convert failures into permanent
          prevention rules.
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          This concept was popularized by Mitchell Hashimoto (creator of Vagrant, Terraform, and
          co-founder of HashiCorp) in his writing on AI-assisted development workflows. The insight
          is deceptively simple: <strong>every agent mistake is a gift</strong>, but only if you have
          a system to convert it into permanent prevention.
        </p>

        <h4>Why most teams never improve</h4>
        <p>
          Without a formal failure loop, the typical workflow is: agent makes mistake &rarr; human
          fixes it &rarr; everyone moves on. The fix addresses the symptom but not the cause. Two
          weeks later, the same mistake happens again &mdash; maybe in a different file, maybe by a
          different agent, maybe by the same agent that has no memory of the previous session. The
          team feels like they&rsquo;re running on a treadmill.
        </p>
        <p>
          The failure loop breaks this cycle by adding two steps between &ldquo;fix it&rdquo; and
          &ldquo;move on&rdquo;: <strong>log it</strong> and <strong>write a rule</strong>. These
          two steps transform a one-time fix into a permanent improvement. The failure log provides
          the audit trail; the rule provides the prevention.
        </p>

        <h4>The anatomy of a good failure log entry</h4>
        <p>
          A failure log entry in <code>docs/failure-log.md</code> should capture four things:
          <strong>what happened</strong> (the observable mistake), <strong>why it happened</strong>
          (the missing context or wrong assumption), <strong>what rule would prevent it</strong>
          (the specific, prescriptive instruction), and <strong>where the rule was added</strong>
          (the file path in <code>docs/rules/</code>). This format makes the log both a diagnostic
          record and a traceability chain from failure to prevention.
        </p>
        <p>
          Over time, the failure log becomes a fascinating artifact. You can read it chronologically
          and watch the harness mature. Early entries tend to be basic (&ldquo;agent didn&rsquo;t
          know which test command to run&rdquo;). Later entries get more sophisticated
          (&ldquo;agent correctly followed the API pattern but missed a subtle edge case in the
          tenant isolation boundary&rdquo;). The progression reveals how the harness is shifting
          the agent&rsquo;s failure mode from &ldquo;basic confusion&rdquo; to &ldquo;subtle edge
          cases&rdquo; &mdash; exactly the trajectory you want.
        </p>

        <h4>Common failure categories</h4>
        <p>
          Most agent failures fall into recognizable categories. <strong>Missing context</strong>
          means the agent didn&rsquo;t know something it needed to (fix: add to AGENTS.md or rules).
          <strong>Wrong assumptions</strong> means the agent guessed instead of checking (fix:
          add explicit instructions). <strong>Convention violations</strong> mean the agent wrote
          working code that doesn&rsquo;t match project style (fix: add or clarify a rule).
          <strong>Boundary violations</strong> mean the agent crossed an architecture line (fix:
          add a Phase 3 test). Categorizing failures helps you see which phases of the harness
          need strengthening.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Steps steps={failureLoopSteps} />

      <div class="tag-list">
        <span class="tag amber">Missing context</span>
        <span class="tag amber">Wrong assumptions</span>
        <span class="tag amber">Convention violations</span>
        <span class="tag amber">Boundary violations</span>
        <span class="tag amber">Redundant code</span>
        <span class="tag amber">Tool misuse</span>
      </div>

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          The failure log is the history; the rules are the accumulated knowledge. Every mistake is
          an investment in the system getting smarter. A team that runs this loop for six months has
          a dramatically more capable agent harness than one that does not &mdash; because every
          mistake has been converted into prevention.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 5 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase5">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 5"
        title="Garbage Collection"
        subtitle="Fight entropy. Keep the harness accurate as the codebase evolves."
        phase={5}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          Documentation, rules, and architecture assertions rot over time. Code changes &mdash;
          files move, modules rename, features are deprecated &mdash; but the docs that reference
          them do not automatically update. Agents reading stale documentation produce wrong code.
          Without active maintenance, the harness itself becomes a source of confusion.
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Every system degrades without maintenance, and a harness is no exception. The term
          &ldquo;garbage collection&rdquo; is borrowed from programming language runtimes, where
          a GC process automatically reclaims memory that&rsquo;s no longer in use. In harness
          engineering, the &ldquo;garbage&rdquo; is stale documentation, outdated rules, and
          boundary tests that no longer match reality.
        </p>

        <h4>Why stale docs are worse than no docs</h4>
        <p>
          When an agent reads documentation that references a file path that no longer exists, or
          a module that was renamed three sprints ago, it doesn&rsquo;t just fail to find the
          information &mdash; it actively generates <em>wrong</em> code based on the stale
          reference. It might create a new file at the old path, import a non-existent module, or
          follow a pattern that was deprecated. Stale documentation is worse than missing documentation
          because it gives the agent <em>confident but incorrect</em> instructions.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is particularly insidious because the mistakes are hard to catch. The agent produced
          code that looks reasonable &mdash; it followed the documented pattern &mdash; but the
          pattern is outdated. A human reviewer who isn&rsquo;t intimately familiar with the recent
          refactor might approve it. The bug only surfaces weeks later, far from its root cause.
        </p>

        <h4>The three garbage collection agents</h4>
        <p>
          Three complementary processes fight entropy at different timescales and different layers
          of the harness:
        </p>
      </div>

      <CardGrid>
        <Card icon="📄" title="Doc Freshness Agent" tag="check-doc-freshness.sh">
          A script that checks every file path referenced in documentation actually exists. Runs
          weekly in CI and on any PR that touches docs. Catches stale references before agents read
          them.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🏗️" title="Architecture Drift Agent" tag="drift detection">
          Checks that the actual codebase structure matches what is documented and tested. Verifies
          boundary tests are still comprehensive as the codebase grows.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="📊" title="Rule Coverage Agent" tag="monthly review">
          Monthly review that analyzes PR review comments for repeated patterns. If reviewers keep
          saying the same thing, it should become a rule.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>

      <div class="prose" style="margin-top: 24px">
        <h4>When to run each agent</h4>
        <p>
          <strong>Doc freshness</strong> should run on every PR that touches documentation and
          on a weekly CI schedule. This catches staleness quickly. <strong>Architecture drift</strong>
          should run when new modules or directories are added &mdash; specifically, when the
          structure of the project changes in ways that might invalidate boundary tests.
          <strong>Rule coverage</strong> is a monthly human-initiated review because it requires
          judgment: reading PR comments, identifying patterns, and deciding what rises to the level
          of a formal rule.
        </p>
        <p>
          The cadence matters. Run garbage collection too rarely and you accumulate debt that
          eventually makes the harness untrustworthy. Run it too aggressively and you spend more
          time maintaining the harness than building features. Weekly doc checks, per-PR drift
          validation, and monthly rule reviews strike a practical balance for most teams.
        </p>
      </div>

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          The harness is only as good as its maintenance. Garbage collection prevents the system
          from degrading back into chaos over time. A harness without GC is like a garden without
          weeding &mdash; it looks fine at first, then slowly becomes unusable as stale information
          misleads agents. The goal is not perfection &mdash; it&rsquo;s preventing the slow decay
          that makes agents unreliable.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

    <!-- ── PHASE 6 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="section" id="phase6">
      <SectionHeader
        label="Phase 6"
        title="Autonomous Execution"
        subtitle="Enable agents to pick up and complete work end-to-end without human decomposition or hand-holding."
        phase={6}
        complete
      />

      <WhyBox>
        <p>
          Even with all the previous phases, agents still needed humans to decompose work into
          tasks, explain what to build, and hand off between different agent modes. The goal was to
          move from &ldquo;agent helps with coding&rdquo; to &ldquo;agent picks up and completes
          work autonomously.&rdquo;
        </p>
      </WhyBox>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Phases 1&ndash;5 create the <em>environment</em> for reliable agent work. Phase 6 creates
          the <em>workflow</em>. The distinction matters: a well-configured environment means agents
          make fewer mistakes, but agents still need someone to tell them <em>what</em> to build
          and <em>in what order</em>. Phase 6 encodes that orchestration into the repository so
          agents can operate with true autonomy.
        </p>

        <h4>Execution plans: the missing link</h4>
        <p>
          Most teams use AI agents by giving them ad-hoc instructions: &ldquo;implement user
          authentication&rdquo; or &ldquo;add a dashboard page.&rdquo; This forces the agent to
          simultaneously figure out <em>what</em> to build, <em>how</em> to decompose it, and
          <em>in what order</em> to do the work. Agents are reasonably good at each of these
          individually, but the combination produces unreliable results &mdash; they might build
          components in the wrong order, skip dependencies, or misunderstand scope.
        </p>
        <p>
          Execution plans solve this by separating <strong>planning</strong> from
          <strong>execution</strong>. A human (or an architect-mode agent) creates a structured
          plan in <code>docs/plans/</code> that decomposes a feature into ordered tasks, each
          with clear acceptance criteria and dependencies. A code-mode agent then picks up the
          plan and executes it step by step. The agent&rsquo;s cognitive load drops dramatically
          because it only needs to focus on one thing: implementing the current task correctly.
        </p>

        <h4>Quality grades: knowing where to be careful</h4>
        <p>
          Not all code is equally trustworthy. Some areas have comprehensive tests, clean
          architecture, and well-documented patterns &mdash; an agent can build on them confidently.
          Other areas are fragile: missing tests, inconsistent patterns, known tech debt. An agent
          that doesn&rsquo;t know the difference will treat all code as equally reliable, leading to
          cascading failures when it builds on a shaky foundation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Quality grades in <code>docs/quality/</code> make this knowledge explicit. Each area of
          the codebase gets a grade from A (rock-solid) to D (fragile/needs rewrite). When an agent
          encounters a Grade D area, it knows to either escalate to a human, proceed with extreme
          caution, or avoid building new features on top of that code. This simple metadata prevents
          the most expensive category of agent failures: working code built on broken foundations.
        </p>

        <h4>Handoff protocols: preserving context across modes</h4>
        <p>
          Complex features often require multiple agent &ldquo;modes&rdquo; &mdash; an architect
          mode to design the approach, a code mode to implement it, and a debug mode to fix issues.
          Without a handoff protocol, context is lost at each transition. The code agent doesn&rsquo;t
          know what tradeoffs the architect considered. The debug agent doesn&rsquo;t know what the
          code agent was trying to accomplish.
        </p>
        <p>
          A handoff protocol is a structured format that captures: what was done, what decisions
          were made (and why), what remains to be done, and any known risks or open questions. Each
          agent writes a handoff note when it finishes, and the next agent reads it before starting.
          This creates a continuous chain of context that survives mode transitions &mdash; no
          information is lost in the handoff.
        </p>
      </div>

      <CardGrid>
        <Card icon="📋" title="Execution Plans" tag="docs/plans/">
          Structured documents in <code>docs/plans/</code> that decompose features into ordered
          tasks with clear acceptance criteria. Agents read a plan and execute it end-to-end without
          human decomposition.
        </Card>
        <Card icon="📊" title="Quality Grades" tag="docs/quality/">
          Per-area quality grades (A/B/C/D) in <code>docs/quality/</code> that tell agents where
          the code is solid (safe to build on) and where it is fragile (needs care or escalation).
        </Card>
        <Card icon="🤝" title="Handoff Protocol" tag="handoff format">
          A standard format for handing work between different agent modes (Architect &rarr; Code
          &rarr; Debug) so context is never lost between transitions.
        </Card>
      </CardGrid>

      <div class="prose" style="margin-top: 24px">
        <h4>The plan lifecycle</h4>
        <p>
          Plans move through two states: <code>Draft</code> and <code>Ready</code>. A
          <code>Draft</code> plan is a work-in-progress &mdash; it may have incomplete task
          definitions, unresolved questions, or missing acceptance criteria. Agents should not
          pick up Draft plans because the ambiguity leads to wasted effort and wrong assumptions.
        </p>
        <p>
          A <code>Ready</code> plan has been reviewed by a human and is fully specified: every
          task has clear acceptance criteria, dependencies are ordered correctly, and scope is
          well-defined. Agents can pick up Ready plans and execute them autonomously with high
          confidence. This two-state system gives humans a clear control mechanism &mdash; promote
          a plan to Ready when you&rsquo;re confident it&rsquo;s correct, and agents will take it
          from there.
        </p>
        <p>
          This separation also creates a natural workflow for teams: product managers or tech leads
          can queue up Draft plans throughout the week, refine them during planning sessions, and
          promote them to Ready. Agents automatically pick up Ready plans, execute them, and submit
          PRs &mdash; creating a pipeline of continuous autonomous delivery.
        </p>
      </div>

      <InsightBox>
        <p>
          Plans in <code>Ready</code> state can be picked up by agents autonomously. Plans in
          <code>Draft</code> state need human review first. Quality grades tell agents whether to
          proceed confidently or escalate to a human. Together, these give you autonomous execution
          with human oversight exactly where it matters.
        </p>
      </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider"></div>

